<td style="vertical-align: top; padding: 0px 0px 20px 0px; border-bottom: 1px solid #cccccc;" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h2><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><a></a><span style="line-height: 22px;">News</span></span></h2>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/udQ000YN4l040h02IMMKT50"
>Sony Pictures Entertainment was recently the victim of a sophisticated and vicious hacking incident</a>, with signs pointing to North Korea as the culprit.
    The attack crippled computer systems, gave the perpetrators access to confidential employee information (including executive salaries), and put unreleased films on file-sharing sites.
    The attack used a so-called wiper virus that erases data and can bring down networks with thousands of computers and prevent companies from being able to conduct business.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Trey Ford, global security strategist at Rapid7, spoke about the possible culprit: &ldquo;Having an angry nation behind the attack makes more sense than an attack by typical profit-driven cybercriminals.
    The attack was clearly aimed to create chaos and disruption &mdash; wiping a master boot record means that upon reboot, the hardware can't be read by the hard drive.
    Destroying a company's machines makes sense for an activist or military operation, either to raise awareness for a specific cause or to destroy an entity's ability to use something.
    This type of destruction clearly means the attackers have &lsquo;no desire to further use that system for themselves,&rsquo; the opposite of anyone doing it for the money.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Ford <a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/d40lM5eQIM0TY00N4i020K0"
>suggests</a> that the possibility of attacks like these should inspire companies to take a hard look at their    
disaster recovery plans.&nbsp;</span></p>
