<td style="vertical-align: top; padding: 0px 0px 20px 0px; border-bottom: 1px solid #cccccc;" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h2><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Community</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">As part of&nbsp;<a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/r40f0T2I0NjlYQK5M00M040"
>Project Sonar</a>, Rapid7 Labs recently released finding from internet-wide scans for NAT-PMP, a protocol implemented by many SOHO-class routers and networking 
   devices.
    It allows firewall and routing rules to be manipulated to enable internal, assumed trusted users behind a NAT device to allow&nbsp;<em>external</em>&nbsp;users to access internal TCP and UDP services for things like Apple's Back to My Mac and file/media sharing services.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">NAT-PMP is a simple but useful protocol, however the majority of the security mechanisms rely on proper implementation of the protocol and a keen eye on the configuration of the service(s) implementing NAT-PMP.&nbsp;Unfortunately,   after 
 performing these harmless scans across UDP port 5351 and testing theories in a controlled lab environment, it was discovered that 1.2 million devices on the public Internet are potentially vulnerable to flaws that allow interception of sensitive, private traffic on the internal and external    
interfaces of a NAT device as well as various other flaws.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">For an in-depth understanding of the uncovered NAT-PMP Implementation and Configuration Vulnerabilities, <a  href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/x0K0000I2g50lQN0k44MYTM"
>view the detailed Rapid7 Labs blog post</a> on the subject.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">You can also visit our community to read up on the <a href=
"http://info.rapid7.com/s0hI0l50YNQl0K0M4M2040T"
>latest developments with the POODLE       
vulnerability</a>.</span></p>
